<br>
There is a reason they demand you tell them upfront everything about the bug.  They dont play games, they always want the ball in their court... it already has them pissed that it has been taken out of their court by a bug (that they let slip no doubt).<br>
<br>
I have been playing EQ a long time.  During the first year, you used to be able to log in on top of people.  i.e., if someone logged into your account, you would not get the message someone was on, you would log in and take over where the other person was.  The original person would be placed in a state of limbo where they could explore the zone indefinitely (sorta like being LD, but not kicked off).  This was not a problem until a monk found a way to exploit this using FD and /q.  I do not remember the monk's name or the exact details, perhaps if you could find a MB archive that dates back 2 years you could find it =P  I assure you this did happen and certain some old skoolers can verify.<br>
<br>
This monk demonstrated it to a GM and emailed Verant like a good player.  The bug was fixed within a week, took that long because Verant had to do a reprograming of how the login server worked.  During that time, they did not give the monk his title, or even get back to him.  So he told Verant he wanted them to fulfil their end of the bargain.  Still no word.  He then gave an ultimadum that he was going to release the bug to the public if they did not fulfil what they promised.  Verant then replied they were confirming it and would indeed fulfil what they had promised.  So the monk did not release it.  Two days after he threatened, servers went down, the bug was fixed, and the monk was banned.  The monk told his story ex post facto but of course by then it was a moot point, as Verant had acted swiftly and connivingly to keep the info secret until they could fix it... and then spite the person that made it known to them just because he wanted them to uphold their promise.<br>
<br>
Maybe he should not have threatened, maybe Verant doesnt give a damn, both probable reasons.  The fact is that there have been many dupe bugs.  It is inevitable, and Verant is not the one that finds them, players do.  This leads me to conclude there have been a lot of people that found bugs, but I have never once heard Verant back that promise up with real evidence of a &quot;hero&quot; that helped keep the world in balance.  Nor have I heard of one on any of the boards I read.  <br>
<br>
